<title>Sun, Moon and stars</title>
<summary><i>Various statements are given with regard to the nature and movements of the celestial bodies. The first of these treats of the Moon and Stars, ending with the &apos;Bushman–rice&apos; Star Canopus (B I. 291-294); the second treats of Sun, Moon, and Stars (B II. 377–379); and the third, of the same (L II.–1. 214 and 215). Prayer to the Star, probably to Canopus, the &apos;Bushman-rice&apos; Star.  (L II.-1. 216 and 217.)</i> Also mentioned are the woman, man and child stars who run into the clouds. These stars go about while people sleep at night.</summary><comments>1) Note on the inside of the back cover of this notebook: &apos;Finished correcting Sept 15/71 from Jantje Toorm himself&apos;, 2)  See also <i>Sun, Moon, and stars</i> and <i>Moon and stars: an incantation</i>, 3) This story is found in Book II-1</comments><date>24 April 1871 (started)</date><storypages>214-217</storypages><category>Celestial bodies and aeroscopy</category><author>||kabbo (Jantje) (II)</author><keyword><kw>prayer</kw><subkw>to star</subkw></keyword>
